In C++, `template<typename T>` is used to define a generic or templated class or function. The `<typename T>` part declares a template parameter named `T`, which can be any valid type in C++.

When you write `template<typename T>` at the beginning of a class or function definition, you are indicating that the code inside the template will be instantiated or generated for different types based on what you specify when you use the template.

Here's an example of a specific usage of the template:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

template<typename T>
class Container {
private:
    T item;

public:
    Container(T value) : item(value) {}

    T getItem() {
        return item;
    }
};

int main() {
    Container<int> intContainer(42);
    std::cout << "Item in intContainer: " << intContainer.getItem() << std::endl;

    Container<std::string> stringContainer("Hello");
    std::cout << "Item in stringContainer: " << stringContainer.getItem() << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we define a generic class `Container` using the `template<typename T>` syntax. The class has a private member variable `item` of type `T`. The constructor takes an argument of type `T`, and the `getItem` method returns the stored item.

In the `main` function, we create instances of `Container` with different types: `int` and `std::string`. When we instantiate `Container<int>`, the `T` in the template is replaced with `int`, and when we instantiate `Container<std::string>`, the `T` is replaced with `std::string`. This allows us to use the same class with different types.

